threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: PE32+ executable (console) x86-64, for MS Windows

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This binary is a specialized credential dumper designed to target the Local Security Authority Subsystem Service (lsass.exe). It performs a classic LSASS memory dumping routine: first, it acquires 'SeDebugPrivilege' to elevate its permissions, then enumerates running processes to locate 'lsass.exe'. It utilizes the 'MiniDumpWriteDump' API with a custom callback (sub_140001000) to capture process memory into a heap-allocated buffer. To evade detection, the dump is encrypted using a simple XOR operation (key 0x36) before being written to a file at 'C:\Users\Public\Downloads\VM25-5-29.log'. This sequence of behaviors is a hallmark of credential harvesting tools used by attackers to obtain Windows authentication secrets.
